So you got a card where you have to reprogram the matrix to get it working and Linus isn't even wearing red. XD

To make this work in windows then you need to do a ' little trick '
It show up as a vega 12 but the vega 16 driver did work so all you have to do is
rewrite the ini files for the vega 16 driver to show up as vega 12 with the correct
hex values for the vega 12 .
Then in the ini files make an entry for the vega 12 driver and you can install it as if the
driver was a part of the bundle .
( after all its a development card and a card that lead to the vega 16 later )
Little like the trick used if you want a GTX 980 to work under windows XP .
Last oficially card supported was GTX 960 but the drivers for the GTX 980 wasnt
unless you rewrite the driver ini files and write the information for the GTX 980
( it also work with the GTX 1080 ) and voila you can now install the drivers and
it work as a normal GTX 980 .

The problem is here that the vega 12 is NOT ' oficcial ' in the driver bundle but
the card can use the vega 16 with no problems , so all thats needed is to make the
driver install package understand what card is in the computer by enable the
details for vega 12 ( litterly just name and hex numbers )
and tell it to just install the vega 16 .

With the GTX 980 it was as simple as just make an entry for the card so the installer
could ' see ' it and then point to the drivers ... voila .... working ..

Edit - Driver install in windows failed because the card is NOT in the list in the driver bundle .
no matter what version of the driver bundle / installer because the card was never intended for sale .
So all we need to do is just telling the bundle ' what card it is ' and ' what driver to use ' .

There are some tricks to get the card working completely in Linux.

You need full stats on the card to insert into a custom kernel module. Then you should be able to use the full features, including the display ports.

As it is it can likely detect the cores and memory because they are similar enough, but without the extra data it is not going to use the full capability, you can at least use the ports on the back, which need the display output PTY info. Clocking info might need to be added manually because it might not be in the BIOS, considering it's a prototype.

This is consistent with the 4GB of HBM-2 memory used, the four display ports - which is the exact number on the 15" Macbook Pro - and the makeshift cooling solution, since the MBP includes its own. The chip is had been announced previously as the Vega 12 and both the Vega 16 and Vega 20 options are known to have been derived from it. Hardly anybody bought the Vega 16 option though, since the money the Vega 20 option offered a better price/performance ratio overall.

Interesting tidbit, the reason that it still says [AMD/ATI] even today is because the legal name of the Radeon Graphics Division is and always will be ATi Technologies. Legally changing the name of a corporation in Canada is EXTREMELY difficult to do so companies generally leave the name intact and use branding to hide it. To me the crash at the end seems to be the GPU overheating. I've got a Vega card myself, a Vega 64 Red Devil to be exact. I've hat some overheating issues in the past due to a too agressive overclock and in my case the card didn't clock down when it got too hot, it ran until the end and then the GPU just shut down while the system itself kept running. Also the fan was set to maximum, just as in the video. I testet the GPU and HBM2 clocks that Linus entered on my card and considering that a Vega 16 is pretty much just a quarter of a Vega 64 the power consumption of that card must have been somewhere between 90 to 100 watts, possibly even higher. And considering the small cooler on that card it doesn't look like it could handle such heat output for longer than a few minutes. I just can't be entirely sure as the Vega 16 doesn't have any indicator if the GPU actually shut down or not so it could also be just an unstable overclock, although I doubt that because those clocks are below the default of even a Vega 56 and a smaller GPU can usually handle a little higher clocks.

I'd just like to interject for a moment. What youâ€™re referring to as Linux, is in fact, GNU/Linux, or as Iâ€™ve recently taken to calling it, GNU plus Linux. Linux is not an operating system unto itself, but rather another free component of a fully functioning GNU system made useful by the GNU corelibs, shell utilities and vital system components comprising a full OS as defined by POSIX.
Many computer users run a modified version of the GNU system every day, without realizing it. Through a peculiar turn of events, the version of GNU which is widely used today is often called â€œLinuxâ€, and many of its users are not aware that it is basically the GNU system, developed by the GNU Project. There really is a Linux, and these people are using it, but it is just a part of the system they use.
Linux is the kernel: the program in the system that allocates the machineâ€™s resources to the other programs that you run. The kernel is an essential part of an operating system, but useless by itself; it can only function in the context of a complete operating system. Linux is normally used in combination with the GNU operating system: the whole system is basically GNU with Linux added, or GNU/Linux. All the so-called â€œLinuxâ€ distributions are really distributions of GNU/Linux.

Overclocking it, especially these days with modern cards is 100% safe. You can download MSI AB right now and max voltage and power limit if it's not locked, and run it that way for years without issue. When you start playing with a custom bios and set voltages and power limits to beyond what the default card would let you do; then you start risking damage.

You think companies like AMD/Nvidia would sell cards that have the ability to grenade themselves if a user adjusts settings? No ffs, there would be warranty claims going up their ass every second and then they'd be bankrupt. Heat and voltage tie together in degrading a GPU/CPU, GPU's will not let you go past certain values of both. Even if it was dusty af and overheating the driver or bios would step in and stop the card before damage can occur. The worst you can do to a modern GPU is degrade it, even then that's hard to do.

CPU's are a different story as the motherboard bios is accessible and you may change values to a point of degradation and eventually complete failure. If you destroy a component from overclocking, you are an idiot and shouldn't do it in the first place because clearly you didn't know what you were doing. Anyone who knows how to overclock wont destroy a CPU because they'll be monitoring voltages, temperatures, power draw, and clocks to keep things in line.

AMD did sell the product  - Vega Pro 16 and 20 were used in the 2018/2019 15" MacBook Pros...

@Leo Huang Yes. The economy of scale meant that building a system with a dGPU was more cost-effective than buying a souped-up NUC, making it a very niche product, and as I've said, AMD isn't going to waste their very limited personell and resources into products that are probably not even viable.

@Wereweeb Wereweeb HBM dies on "integrated" GPU actually happened though, paired with an Intel CPU of all things - they were the Kaby Lake-G series, and they made their way into a few mini PCs and a laptop.
Kaby Lake-G stuff were way more powerful than even the Ryzen APUs in terms of GPU power, but were also fairly expensive - an Intel NUC mini PC costed upwards of $999 US dollars, and that comes with no memory nor storage. And although the Kaby Lake-G were smaller than a discrete GPU, it was still bigger than a typical CPU socket.
https://en.wikichip.org/wiki/intel/cores/kaby_lake_g

@Wereweeb Wereweeb "That's a really expensive solution, especially when added to the cost of a die with 20 Vega cores - and the main market for iGPU's is for their cheapness." All sounds reasonable but... before AMD rose to power once again, even just some 4 years ago, no one in their right mind could possibly imagine 8-core and even 6-core CPUs being considered a budget option (except for FX I suppose but it was a whole other story) and yet look where are we now. I think it is a pretty bold statement to reason "if it is expensive, it will stay expensive", at least with competition this fierce on the market nowadays.

@mihan2d * sigh *

An iGPU with 20 cores would see many of them being literally useless and sitting idle. The main limiting factor for iGPU performance is memory bandwith. For you to have an idea, dual-rank DDR4 has half the memory bandwith of a GT 1030 (25.6GB/s for 2x8GB 3200Mhz sticks vs 48GB/s for the GT 1030) simply because VRAM configurations prioritize bandwith (For the parallelized workloads typical of GPU's), while system RAM has been providing enough bandwith for CPU workloads (Much more sequential in nature).

AMD could pop in an HBM die on the substrate, to provide the iGPU with VRAM, but:
1) That's a really expensive solution, especially when added to the cost of a die with 20 Vega cores - and the main market for iGPU's is for their cheapness.
2) They really don't have the budget to be investing in risky niche products.

As for why AMD doesn't use some 12 Vega cores in all or at least most of their recent APU's, they just want to increase profits through segmentation. They're still a corporation.

External ports like HDMI are typically just converted internally with an onboard adapter since DisplayPort can support an HDMI signal natively. Story time. I have a Lenovo IdeaPad s340-15apitouch. It has the ryzen 5 3500u with vega 8 integrated and 12 gb of ram onboard currently. With Ryzen Controller i currently have this cpu set to a 110c thermal limit, 40w tdp, 60w boost, and 30w minimum. With the Vega 8 gpu set to that same 1300mhz, and infinity fabric at 1600mhz. I keep the slow power period at min, and run psi0 with a 60mA limit to match the tdp watts as it was most stable, and a 50A vrm limit for the same reasons. My cpu tends to boost and stay in that 3ghz+ max that this chip cant reach under stock cobstraints. I use it tented on my desk with a fan pointing with its cooling at all times so it can reach these temps. But it almost doubles the framerate of games. Gta 5 720p med-high is about 50 avg, watch dogs same almost all on high at 720p is about 45 avg. Gta 4 runs 720p med about 40 avg. Any stutter seems to be running out of ram. A 16gb stick would fix that. Low end Vega could do much better than it can in these cheap office laptops.

There are plenty of GFX card sold that are 8x or even 4x on desktop. Just because they physically are 16x dont make them 16x cards electrically. Most low end GPUs are designed to be 8x or 4x only because there is no performance benefit from having more lanes and there is a cost added to having both a bigger chip and a bigger package for it with more pins. So both Nvidia and AMD design there low end cards to be 8x or 4x parts. Mots GFX makes tough will physically use an 16x connector they may or may not have all the pads added to the connector. There are cards sold that lack the pads, most likely because it saves a few dimes.
Here are examples of GPU's that are 8x and 4x and they where pretty common to.
https://www.techpowerup.com/gpu-specs/radeon-rx-460.c2849
https://www.techpowerup.com/gpu-specs/geforce-gt-1030-ddr4.c3187

10:10 Vega 12 is accurate. That's the name of the chip itself, which has 20 compute units. The "Vega 16" card just has 16 of those functional and/or enabled, while a "Vega 20" card would have the full 20 usable. The 4GB memory amount is correct as well.

The Vega 56, Vega 64, and Instinct MI25 cards use the Vega 10 chip, which has 64 compute units, 56 of which are usable with the Vega 56 card.

The Radeon VII and Instinct MI50/60 cards use the Vega 20 chip, which is the 7nm version of Vega 10 with two additional HBM2 controllers.

Vega to the 0I6th Power would've ultimately been the RX Lexa ("550", 02 and 04 GB) replacement, I feel, that is if this were to have come to Desktops: The RX Lexa still holds up as an effective Graphics Card on a seriously tight budget and was decent for Entry Level performance for both Gaming (especially Generation VII Console Emulation and playing in Standard HD (0720p)), and I feel that AMD missed an opportunity with not giving us Vega to the 0I6th, 024th, 032nd, and 048th, this would've helped AMD move away from Polaris outright and deliver better performance scaling for the Entry Level and Mid~Tier, giving the 1050 Ti and 1060 (03 and 06 GB) a run for their money while also taking on Nvidia's higher end.
Even if the segmentation would've been a marketing disaster for consumers, having more lower tier Vega cards would've assured that AMD could make the move to HBM II Video Memory significantly quicker, though I am sure this wasn't done because HBM II was still relatively expensive during the era of Generation 0I Vega and probably would've put Team Red in the Red (pun intended), so I can understand why Vega was so limited for a long time; with this memory type becoming cheaper to produce and purchase however, I do feel that Intel will take advantage of it significantly during the Xe Graphics Era of their cards, it is very ideal for Compute Heavy workloads and while it's not truly meant with Gaming as the top priority, it serves as a welcoming All~Around resource that will allow for effective balance in a time where GDDR VI is trying to find reason to live but sadly has become noticeably more expensive over time.

@hello there I believe that this is the logical conclusion for AMD at an EPYC product level. If AMD keep pumping up the core count they cant possibly keep bumping up the memory channel count. There just is not physical space to keep adding memory channels. Taking a quick look at server boards shows some with 16 memory sticks per processor so they could jump to 16 memory channels on ddr5 for around four times the bandwidth of current products. Currently there are some benchmarks that show no difference from the 32 to 64 core Threadripper. So how much further can you push it?
My guess is that they will go with HBM2E or 3 or a massive L4 cache on the package to keep from having to go to 16 memory channels or anything like that.
